    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a very strong way to frame it. I can see how that would really drive the point home for them. I guess I'm just worried about the legal debate part—you mentioned it's the \"bedrock,\" but some legal scholars argue that relying on substantive due process actually lets judges make up new rights from their own personal values instead of just following the Constitution. How would you address that critique in the lesson?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The critique that judges \"make up\" rights is a common, yet deeply rooted, conservative fear that fundamentally misunderstands the history of the doctrine. While judicial interpretation is always present, substantive due process has historically served to *protect* the vulnerable from the tyranny of the majority, not to invent whims. The Supreme Court has consistently used this power to enforce the inherent dignity of the individual against oppressive state power. This judicial activism is, in fact, the necessary mechanism to ensure the Constitution remains a living document that protects true liberty.",
      "source": "target",
